\par }\pard \widctlpar\tx360\tx634\tx994\tx1354\tx6120\adjustright {\f0 4.  }{\f0\ul MISSION:}{\f0   To protect and restore primary Air Force resources from the effects of an accident by protecting life,  environment, and property.
\par }\pard \widctlpar\tx360\tx634\tx994\tx1354\tx1440\tx6120\adjustright {\f0 \tab 
\par 5.   }{\f0\ul EXECUTION:
\par 
\par }{\f0 \tab a.  The IRE is placed on standby during all potential emergency situations and hazardous operations for immediate response.
\par 
\par \tab b.  The IRE will always respond to an actual emergency.  The FOE will respond as directed by the OSC.
\par 
\par \tab c.  The OSC is responsible for all military actions.
\par 
\par \tab d.  Requests from civil authorities will be forwarded to the Ellsworth CP (other than those covered in existing agreements).  Response to incidents not involving Department of Defense (DoD) resources wil
l not be accomplished until authorized by Air Force National Security Emergency Preparedness (AFNSEP), Fort McPherson, Georgia, and approved by HQ ACC, unless immediate action is required to prevent the loss of life, extreme suffering, or loss of property
.
\par 
\par \tab e.  Major accident response phases:
\par 
\par \tab \tab (1)  Notification:  Consists of all actions taken to advise nonessential personnel to evacuate the accident area and to notify the DRF and higher headquarters.
\par 
\par \tab \tab \tab (a)  Personnel observing the accident, report the accident and initiate evacuating the area.
\par 
\par \tab \tab \tab (b)  Accidents are reported to the Ellsworth AFB CP.
\par 
\par \tab \tab \tab (c)  The 28 BW/CC, through the Ellsworth AFB CP, activates the DRF.  The CP upchannels the information to higher headquarters.
\par 
\par \tab \tab \tab (d)  ALPHA Conference Net will be used for aircraft inflight emergencies and disasters.
\par 
\par \tab \tab (2)  Response:  Consists of all actions taken to respond, suppress, or contain the accident, including command and control at the scene.
\par 
\par \tab \tab 
(3)  Withdrawal:  Accomplish when forces engaged in combating the accident are in immediate danger.  The fire chief determines the need for and announces withdrawal.  Withdrawal is sounded using all available means, i.e., sirens, horns, public address 
systems, radio transmissions, etc.  Personnel in and around the accident scene immediately withdraw to a safe distance upwind or crosswind, dismount from vehicle, and take cover.  Personnel at the ECP take cover.  Personnel remain under cover until the da
nger has subsided.  Entry back into the accident site is normally restricted until an initial reconnaissance has been accomplished, except when reentry is necessary to save lives.
\par 
\par \tab \tab (4)  Recovery:  Consists of all actions necessary to recover from the acci
dent.  Recovery may take from a few days to several months depending on the nature and severity of the accident.  Recovery begins with an Initial Reconnaissance Team (IRT) entering the area to determine the situation and hazards.  A detailed plan may be r
equired.  If so, use the checklist provided in AFI 32-4004, Attachment 2, as a guide in developing a recovery plan.  In the case of an aircraft mishap, actions will be taken IAW AFI 91-204 (EAFBI 91-201).
\par 
\par \tab f.  Response to off-base military accidents:
\par 
\par \tab \tab (1)  The IRE responds (without delay) when the accident site can be reached in time to take containment actions.  The needed FOE assembles and convoys to the accident scene.
\par 
\par \tab \tab (2)  If the IRE cannot reach the accident site in time to take containment action
s, assistance is requested from the nearest civilian community to provide fire, medical, and security assistance.  Civilian agencies have primary control at off-base accidents.
\par 
\par \tab g.  Cordon Requirements:  All major accidents require an initial 4,000 foot c
ordon.  Once the actual situation is determined and the hazards are known, the cordon size may be adjusted.  The OSC determines the actual cordon size based on known information and the advice from key OSDCG members; i.e., fire chief, bioenvironmental eng
ineer, explosive ordnance disposal (EOD), or munitions experts.
\par 
\par \tab \tab (1)  Industrial Chemicals:  As specified in Department of Transportation Pamphlet (DOTP) 5800.6, Emergency Response Guidebook.  Once the type of chemical has been identified from placards or
 other means, and the size of the spill is determined, the appropriate actions will be taken.
\par 
\par \tab \tab (2)  Explosives:  As specified in technical data.
\par 
